[1/4] Recently I spent some time with the good folks at Cascade Medical Center in Cascade, Idaho for the @nytimes. My wife works at a rural hospital in the Columbia Gorge so this story was especially interesting.

Rural hospitals all across the US are facing tough decisions as pandemic funding fades away but a new federal program is offering a lifeline with a heavy cost. Emily Baumgaertner writes, “The program, which invites more than 1,700 small institutions to become federally designated ‘rural emergency hospitals,’ would inject monthly payments amounting to more than $3 million a year into each of their budgets, a game-changing total for many that would not only keep them open but allow them to expand services and staff. In return, they must commit to discharging or transferring their patients to bigger hospitals within 24 hours.”

Photos in order — 
1. Dan Rosbrugh at his home in Cascade, ID. A recent patient at Cascade Medical Center who might not be here without their inpatient care.
2. Heather Lewis, PA, at Cascade Medical Center
3. Aaron Cook in the ER. Aaron describes himself as a ‘frequent flyer’ at the hospital who has battle an opioid addiction and was recently admitted after a car accident. 
4. Deer in front of the medical center
5. Rural road outside Cascade, ID

Thanks to all the nurses and doctors that let me roam around the hospital. And super fun to work with @mcmarbled and @ragtimebilliepeaches on this one.

2/4] Recent work for the @nytimes in Cascade, Idaho. Over 180 rural hospitals have closed in the United States since 2005, according to a recent analysis, with a record 19 closings in 2020 alone…In 10 states, at least 40 percent of rural hospitals are in danger: In Kansas, 16 could close within three years; in Mississippi, 24. 

For 46 million Americans, rural hospitals are a lifeline, yet an increasing number of them are closing. The federal government is trying to resuscitate them with a new program that offers a huge infusion of cash to ease their financial strain. But it comes with a bewildering condition: They must end all inpatient care. The program, which invites more than 1,700 small institutions to become federally designated ‘rural emergency hospitals,’ would inject monthly payments amounting to more than $3 million a year into each of their budgets, a game-changing total for many that would not only keep them open but allow them to expand services and staff. In return, they must commit to discharging or transferring their patients to bigger hospitals within 24 hours. Words by Emily Baumgaertner

Years ago, I spent a week with Scott Lindquist in Alaska for @outsidemagazine. Lindquist, who is legally blind, harvests glacier ice in Prince William Sound for a local distillery. It was a wild assignment that involved interesting characters, an ER visit, and a stressful midnight snowmobile ride over thinly covered lakes with a blind man at the helm in search of the northern lights. We didn’t see them.

Recent work for the @nytimes. Following Eric Adam’s legislation to fight rats, I visited Shawn Woods in his home near Monmouth, Oregon. Woods, a successful YouTube channel host with over a million subscribers, posts a weekly (or more) video discussing traps from around the world. He has become an expert in both the design and effectiveness of traps, some of which from the 1800s are worth $10,000 or more. What a strange and fun assignment. In 2021, I was invited to join a bison hunt on the edge of Yellowstone National Park in Montana with enrolled members of the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian Reservation (CTUIR). I spent a week in -25° temps barely avoiding frostbite while changing film. We watched and waited for the bison to cross out of the Park and onto Forest Service land where they could be shot. They never crossed.

That year, and the next, the number of bison culled (shot or trapped) was extremely low. In 2022, only 49 bison were removed from the Yellowstone herd. That’s far below the goal of 25% to keep the carrying capacity sustainable, according to National Park Service officials. In 2023, I joined the same group and saw a record number bison migrate from the park boundaries resulting in over 1,100 shot by both native and non-native hunters.

How we manage bison going forward remains an open question. Some tribes and environmentalists see them as wildlife and have pushed to open public lands to migrating bison. Ranchers (and other environmentalists) see them as livestock, best raised with fences and boundaries. At the center of the debate are the tribes who have always held bison at the heart of their culture and whose opinions vary. 

I brought this story to the @nytimes and am grateful to see it in print and online. Thanks to all those who welcomed me to join their group and to @mcmarbled for the assist.

Montana 2014, 2021, 2023 for the @nytimes. I was on an assignment in Montana in 2014 and photographed members of the Blackfeet Nation organizing a massive collection of slaughtered bison heads for ceremonial purposes. An obviously striking scene, I filed it away in the list of ‘interesting things to revisit’. I went back that same year on my own to spend time with a rancher family that was ardently opposed to bison reintroduction on public lands. They were gracious, hard-working and welcoming in every regard. I woke at all times of the night to watch them help cows give birth in sub-zero temps. With a few more trips here and there, I kept adding to the series over the years and figured it would resurface at some point. Or not. Plenty don’t. Fast forward to 2021 and 2023, I was back in Montana for the bison hunt featured this week and was able to see a grandfather hunt with his grandson and harvest their first bison. The archive of people and issues, or simply unique stories that interest me, grows and occasionally, very occasionally, the series (or a piece of the series) makes its way into the public. It’s always refreshing to see but like C.P. Cavafy wrote in 1911, [extremely summarized and paraphrased] ‘it ain’t about the destination’. @modocstories

We’ve been photographing and reporting on the story of Apalachicola oysters for over a decade. In 2013 we finished a month-long canoe trip (and documentary film, Who Owns Water) in the Bay with Kendall Shoelles, a lifelong oysterman. We’ve been back numerous times to the Gulf Coast over the years as we watched the oyster populations decline and ultimately crash, leading to the closure of all oystering in the Bay in 2020. 

Yesterday, David’s piece for the @bittersoutherner, “The Last Oyster Tongers of Apalachicola”, was nominated as a finalist for the prestigious James Beard Foundation Award for Feature Reporting. It’s a good piece worth reading so google it and find it. @davidhanson3 @modocstories 

Also, shout out to @charles.bethea, a good friend and writer for the @newyorkermag, who was nominated as well.

Recent work for @esquire with @jacksholmes. Two and half years ago, Oregon tried something new becoming the only state to decriminalize simple drug possession.  Measure 110, passed in 2020, takes tax proceeds from legal marijuana sales and put them towards treatment for more serious substance abuse. It’s a good read about the extremely difficult situation without any clear answers. Check it out in this month’s Esquire.
